            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                <p>Ogham: No complete translation is suggested for the Ogham inscription <q><persName xml:lang="pgl">Pumpeius</persName> seems likely to have been rendered in the ogam but there seems to be no correlation to the remainder of the two inscriptions</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" n="2">
                    <p>Latin: <persName xml:lang="pgl">Pumpeius</persName> <persName xml:lang="pgl">Carantorius</persName> (lies here)</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                        <p>The Ogham inscription appears to correspond to the Roman-letter inscription in its first half <q>the ogam P[O]P[, if correctly restored...may preserve the original vowel <foreign xml:lang="la">Pompeius</foreign>...[most likely] the omission of the /m/ is due to Vulgar Latin as in SEPRONIVS (<hi rend="italic">RIB 1:</hi> no. 686), and Continental forms such as <foreign xml:lang="la">Popeianus</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="la">Pepeia</foreign>...If POPIAS is the correct reading, the -AS may be the Irish nominative ending corresponding to Latin <foreign xml:lang="la">-us</foreign> and IA rather than EA could be a hypercorrect spelling...The <foreign xml:lang="sga">forfid</foreign><!--NEED TO CHECK IMAGES OF THIS ONE!--> for P is one of the additional ogam letters invented for this un-Irish sound</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440-1). The rest of the inscription does not appear to correspond to the Roman-letter inscription. <q>ROLACUN...offers the Irish etymology *<foreign xml:lang="pgl">Ro-ola-kun-</foreign>, 'very large hound'... ILLUNA could be related to the OI name <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Illan(n), Elann</foreign> and word <foreign xml:lang="pgl">ela</foreign> 'swan', as in <hi rend="italic">CIIC:</hi> no. 79, ELUNA in Ireland</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 441).</p>
                        <p>In the Roman-letter inscription, <q>PVMPEIVS for <foreign xml:lang="la">Pompeius</foreign> may show the Welsh development of /um/ [from] /om/...CARANTORIVS is definitely not Irish; it is the forerunner of OW <foreign xml:lang="owl">Cerenhir</foreign>, W. <foreign xml:lang="cy">Cerennhyr</foreign>...such names in <foreign>-orius</foreign> have been much discussed</q> but no definitive interpretation of its significance is offered (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 440-1).</p>
            </div>
